<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1041> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1041 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-05T14:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "William F. Temple" ;
    schema:dateCreated "1966"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Four-sided Triangle" ;
    schema:review "This was supposed to be old, as in really old WW era, science fiction. And while it was certainly slow, what came across was a story. Something that preceded many other ideas. A clone of your loved one who doesn't love you back, and what might that clone then do -- won't it love you? A simple premise that plays out as a social drama. Yes, there are elements of science fiction still in there, nearly half a century past. The sexism of the times does come across in places, sometimes strongly, such as when referring to asking permission from 'him' about 'her', but there is not a lot of it beyond the phrasing. I picked up a cheap copy - hardly 3 euros courtesy of the British Library. So this was a good exercercise in reading some older literature with a still interesting story."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1041"^^xsd:anyURI .

