    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "The Census Taker" ;
    schema:review "Deep story that demands thoughtfulness. But also difficult to read and understand the many many layers of thought behind each action, and the subtlety of shaping the story in a certain way. Are we sure we understood things correctly? Or do we just prefer to have a happy ending after all?"@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1064"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1065> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1065 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-06-30T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "John Scalzi" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2022"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "The Kaiju Preservation Society" ;
    schema:review "Not all books have to be deep complex stories and full of amazing world-building. Sometimes a book is like a good snack -- it is just enough to get you through a flight or a beach day. This is a good book for that sort of thing. There's that silly bit of pushing the plot along and then there;s some sprinkled bits about modernity - like mentioning the president since this book was written during covid. The overall pace moves along just well enough to not delve too deep nor bore you. "@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1065"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1066> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1066 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-01T02:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "T. Kingfisher" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2022"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "Nettle & Bone" ;
    schema:review "Fantasy but touched with reality. Knowing more about the hard choices one makes, especially as a woman, really shapes the story beyond just magic and action or whatever typical things are. Really nicely put together. Enough nuance to have things be conscious but not enough to feel in your face or that it isn't part of the story. The ending was a bit of a rush, but it still was enjoyable. In a weird way reminded me of reading Earthsea series."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1066"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1067> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1067 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-17T17:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Tom Watson" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2022"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "Metronome" ;
    schema:review "A well written book with a simple premise, though I felt that some things were not as well developed. For example, without spoilers, there were plot devices that 'just worked' and had to work for the story to progress. That felt unrealistic. Apart from that this is a well written book and the two characters felt well thought out. Aside, this book should not be classified as sci-fi because there is a very little soft touch of actual science fiction here. It is still a good fiction book."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1067"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1068> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1068 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-07T20:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Susanna Clarke" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2020"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "Piranesi" ;
    schema:review "The opening segment blasts you straight into a familiar feeling. Its a house with seemingly infinite rooms. There are variations, things of interest, and explorations. Hidden knowledge. Biomes. Wonders. What it reminded me of immediately was it someone had taken Borges' works and decided to really get into it. But there's more to this than just that. Towards the end, things collapse down into more predictable fantasies. But the writing is sharp, the nature of wonder and innocence and being human, that draws itself out in the confines of the House, is really the highlight. Can we see the wonders that pass by us everyday? Sometimes it takes another world to realise that."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1068"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1069> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:1069 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-07-06T14:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Simon Jimenez" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2020"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:DublinLibrary ;
    schema:name "The Vanished Birds" ;
    schema:review "The setting of the book is definitely within the bounds of scifi, what with the ability of a boy to teleport to any place he wants. But the core of the book is what it means to be a human in a society -- especially one that functions capitalistically. The boy is now a resource, for the benefit of mankind's progress of course, and the characters lives and decisions are all invisibly moved by the hand that takes things with an immeasurably invisible force and is reluctant to return any of it. There are colonies, corporations, subservient governments, and humans stuck in this way of life. The writing could have been better, the story does move at a very slow pace. But its undeniable what the book is."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/1069"^^xsd:anyURI .

