<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/868> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:868 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2023-04-01T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Salman Rushdie" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:isPartOf hplist:cork ;
    schema:name "Victory City" ;
    schema:review "I didn't know a new book from Salman Rushdie had been published until I came across while walking through the book store. Bought it on an impulse - how could I resist. Looking forward to the mesmerising delight that is Rushdie's linguistic forte, I was quite surprised to discover that this was an incredibly clever and well-woven tale of modernity spun into the fabric of ancient Indian history. So much to easily miss, not notice, and realise that this is a really well written story. I missed the poetic language that evoke a love for reading, but the story itself being set in parallels to India mythologies was intriguing in itself. Still a good read - but I want to go get another Rushdie book to satiate my appetite for the language from Midnight's Children and Shame - which I immensely enjoyed."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/868"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/869> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:869 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2023-04-15T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Sheri S. Tepper" ;
    schema:dateCreated "1989"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Grass" ;
    schema:review "This is a well-written book with characters that are multi-dimensional, a world and setting that is explored in depth, and a sci-fi narrative that has sociological ecological analogies. The only thing that felt out of place was the setting of social constructs based on aristrocatic fox hunting, though I understand how that setting made sense for the story. Enjoyable, though the novel is a bit long and takes its time to showcase the mysteries. I can imagine this as being an excellent TV series."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/869"^^xsd:anyURI .

