    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Cory Doctorow" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "The Lost Cause" ;
    schema:review "I didn't know this book was YA (Young Adult), so while reading it I constantly kept being annoyed by the language and the juvenile characters. When I found out, I changed my perspective about. Overall, its a good optimistic story set in a rough time, where the government has got its bearings on correct, and everything is green and clean. Still, not a great book. Might have been interesting when I was younger and not as matured."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/916"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/917> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:917 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-12-21T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating2 ;
    schema:author "R. Trebor Scholz" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:name "Own this!: How platform cooperatives help workers build a democratic Internet" ;
    schema:review "The topic is of great interest to me, however the book never really gets into an exploration of how co-operatives work or what challenges they face. We get lots and lots of examples and mentions without any real takeaways. At times it felt unnecessary to see blockchain mentioned in places without exploring all the other governance mechanisms. Not recommended for reading."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/917"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/918> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:918 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-03-21T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Matteo Pasquinelli" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:name "The Eye of the Master: A Social History of Artificial Intelligence" ;
    schema:review "I got this book because I saw it being highly recommended somewhere. I didn't remember where or why when I started reading it. So when I was suddenly bombarded with the history of labour and how the word algorithm has been defined and used to also mean the processes and the knowledge of carrying out work, it was interesting to read. However, the book slowly builds its way to the modern times, making the case that algorithms have always reflected the work done by humans i.e. labour and that the role of machines has always been based on the division of labour as a means to reuse the knowledge of the collective. I'm no sociologist, but okay, let's see where this goes. Then suddenly the book gets to the modern AI era and we don't get as many details or as detailed an explanation. I read a review that called this book \"blue balling for reading\" and that's exactly the feeling I have. Disappointing that right where it would have been most useful, it gives up and finishes."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/918"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/919> a hpcom:Book,
