    schema:dateCreated "2014"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "The Causal Angel" ;
    schema:review "The third book in the series - it coninues throwing advanced physics concepts (while making up many more) in an entertaining way. Enjoyed it thoroughly even if there were some hiccups to understand what exactly was happening (in terms of the technologies being used). This link: http://lewyland.blogspot.com/2015/10/hannu-rajaniemis-quantum-thief-trilogy.html came in handy for later recapping the sheer breadth of creativity in the series."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/936"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/937> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:937 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2024-06-14T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Stephen Baxter" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2014"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Ultima" ;
    schema:review "I bought this sequel immediately after finishing Proxima. The story ended without answers about the aliens, the space-connecting hatches, and the apparent nature of hatches as changing universes or travelling across them. This book promised the answers. And it did deliver them. I didn't really like the historical spacefarers - they seemed to distract from the story itself which was about these world hopping hatch building aliens. I wanted more of that. The ending (spoilers) deals with the end of universes and the nature of multiple universes (parallel, yes) and how one theory for how they end can be made."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/937"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/938> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:938 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2024-08-11T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating2 ;
    schema:author "Hannu Rajaniemi" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2018"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Summerland" ;
    schema:review "Coming hot off the Quantum Thief trilogy which was heavy on epic physics and quantum technologies - this was a book I was looking forward with high expectations. Unfortunately, the imply but don't tell much style doesn't work when talking about the afterlife - the more the world and underlying physics is hinted at the more there are questions raised. The story was not really compelling or interesting - maybe it is for people interested in British cultural settings. To me, this was a book that could have been so much more because the ideas are cool, but the execution is utterly not."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/938"^^xsd:anyURI .

