<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/968> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:968 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-01-15T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Blake Crouch" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2022"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Upgrade" ;
    schema:review "Tell me if you've heard this before: a magic pill or drug or whatever that makes the person super smart, strong, or basically a superhuman, and then chaos ensues. That's the premise of this book. We have some (scientifically structured) gene editing that's been used by the black market to do stuff. The details are a nice touch, with several things clearly coming across as a well thought through plot structure. But the basic premise and the writing style still falls quite short of being an excellent book. This is great beach or plane material - read it while you're tired or don't want to think too much. Because if you do, you will see glaring plot holes and problems erupt everywhere. But if you don't, you get to enjoy a nice ride."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/968"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/969> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:969 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-11-23T13:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating5 ;
    schema:author "Oliver Burkeman" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2021"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:name "Four Thousand Weeks" ;
    schema:review "This book effectively points out that you have a limited amount of time and that you should be aware of it. That's pretty much it. There isn't too much of a beating around the bush or hammering it over your head. You listen to what the person has to say, go yes that makes sense, and then go over to mull over it. I did that, read the book once, thought about it, then read it again to make notes for future reference. Worthwhile reading if the topic has been on your mind."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/969"^^xsd:anyURI .

