    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Sarah Pinsker" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2021"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "We are satellites" ;
    schema:review "The book is about Pilots - a neuralink type tech that gets you alert but not superintelligent. But the book is not about the tech at all. Instead, its about the normal people who have to put this in, have to face the subjective experiences of living in a world that increasingly considers having this as ableism and a status symbol. Brilliant restrained take. The only thing that felt off was the ending which became cliche for me, but did not detract from the rest of the book."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/983"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/984> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:984 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-12-27T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating4 ;
    schema:author "Olga Tokarczuk" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2022"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction ;
    schema:name "The Empusium" ;
    schema:review "A horror story? By Olga Tokarczuk?! Yes please! After 'Drive your Plow over the Bones of the Dead', I was excited to see this. Half way through the book, after several passing references to ghosts, spirits, and in general uncomfortable circumstances but no actual horror, it struck me that the horror was more psychological. All the men were afraid of the women! Its not an accurate description of the book, but its a keen, wise, and clever take on storytelling that hides the real realisations until the very end, but also asks the reader to reflect on their own as characters become more familiar and exposed."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/984"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/985> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:985 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-12-25T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Paul Lynch" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction ;
    schema:name "Prophet Song" ;
    schema:review "A strangely intense novel about what I would also have called dystopian, but the author states its not dystopian if its already happening somewhere. The book is set in Ireland amidst a future where a far-right government has taken over and we have a police agency who can simply disappear people. Its authoritarian fascism in a place where its really difficult to imagine it. I wanted to know about how something like this happened. But the book doesn't really give any glimpses in to the history. There's also a surprising aspect where we only really see people who are against the power. The writing is good, it really creates a sense of urgency and stress that resonates with the happenings in each page and chapter. Interesting read, but didn't really stick with me in the end."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/985"^^xsd:anyURI .

