    hpcom:date_book_read "2026-01-02T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating5 ;
    schema:author "James S. A. Corey" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2015"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Leviathan Falls" ;
    schema:review "The last book in the series of 9 books. Incredible expectations. Lots of loose ends to tie up. Will it end with a satisfying exposition or will things be hurriedly resolved off-screen. Reading was exciting, the story kept pushing the pace so there never was a feeling that where's my ending. I could happily have read a couple more novels in continuation. And yes, the ending does satisfy things in a way that doesn't leave much to regret. Really solid writing, and what a job to deliver 9 books!"@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/991"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/992> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:992 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-11-30T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating5 ;
    schema:author "Adrian Tchaikovsky" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2025"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Shroud" ;
    schema:review "The best way I can describe this book is as if Jules Verne and Stephen Baxter had an adventure story written for Star Trek. Its simultaneously hard science fiction, as hard as it can get, with just a fantastically new and alien perspective on life and intelligence, and also a commentary of society and a truly grim outlook on the corporate capitalist nature of economy. The book itself is about aliens that evolved to treat the EM spectrum as communications medium without any sunlight, meaning only things that interact specifically with the EM bands are relevant. Human meatbags are not. Human made vehicles are. An adventure across the planet ensues. Brilliant, and extremely rewarding. I also somehow read this (hopefully) as a link to the next book in the Children of Time series. I'm going to be hunting for Tchaikovsky's books - the man has a talen for rapidly producing intelligent situations and writing multiple books in a year."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/992"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/993> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:993 ;
    hpcom:book_owned_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:PhysicalBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-10-04T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating1 ;
    schema:author "Lee Min-ye" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2023"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookFiction,
        hpcom:BookSciFi ;
    schema:name "Dallergut Dream Department Store" ;
    schema:review "The premise of the book seemed alluring. A department store where you go buy dreams? An economy built on emotional reactions? A character plot promising hidden wisdom and a takedown of busy lifebodies? Sold! I bought the physical book. Turned out to be a dud. The premise seemed exceedingly made up and changing arbitrarily as if we are kids learning from story book time. There is no details given to characters beyond what seems like a single facet that you hold them to for the entire story. Feels too emotional reaction driven rather than being about actual ideas or stories. Disappointing."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/993"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/994> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
        hpcom:RenderedItem,
        schema:Book ;
    hpcom:book_id hpcom:994 ;
    hpcom:book_read_medium hpcom:EBook ;
    hpcom:book_status hpcom:book-read ;
    hpcom:date_book_read "2025-11-01T00:00:00"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:aggregatedRating hptag:Rating3 ;
    schema:author "Sandra Uwiringiyimana, Abigail Pesta" ;
    schema:dateCreated "2017"^^xsd:int ;
    schema:genre hpcom:BookNonFiction ;
    schema:name "How dare the sun rise" ;
    schema:review "This was part of the bookclub, so gave it a go. Was really into the story because its told so well, and its so human and real, and just made me more aware of different perspectives that I thought I knew but benefitted from seeing it from someone else's experiences. The story is about how the author escapes from a war torn country where they are effectively cuturally and socially uprooted, and their move to America with their parents, the adaption, and rising through sheer dedication and mindset. Admirable, and a good look on the world being more than a few ideas and people despite what we get exposed to."@en ;
    schema:url "https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/994"^^xsd:anyURI .

<https://harshp.com/hobbies/books/995> a hpcom:Book,
        hpcom:BookReading,
